					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/julibe" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1414220); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1414220&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203968" alt="Julibe" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1414220)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/julibe" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1414220); return false;" >Julibe</a></span> <span class="odate time_1344676091 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Aug 2012 09:08</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1534115">
									

<p>This, and original SCP are both very good. It's cool to have something that fits the old folklore feel and still fits the SCP universe as well.</p>
<p>Silly question of the day: What if, instead of capturing the third in his sack, he were to use the final use to capture himself? On the one hand, it's a silly idea, on the other hand maybe it's what the brothers want from him, as it's a sort of humble resignation, a recognition that he can never beat them again, will never lure them in, and can only save humanity by meekly succumbing to them the way he didn't the first time. Unlike 'catching death in a sack', which even if it's for his own destruction is still a grandiose path, it would be a real admission of defeat and surrender.</p>

							</div>

								
					
